Massachusetts Institute of Technology Department of Electrical Engineering & Computer Science 6.041/6.431: Probabilistic Systems Analysis (Fall 2010) Problem Set 5 Due October 18, 2010

2. Paul is vacationing in Monte Carlo. The amount X (in dollars) he takes to the casino each evening is a random variable with the PDF shown in the figure. At the end of each night, the amount Y that he has on leaving the casino is uniformly distributed between zero and twice the amount he took in.¶

(a) Determine the joint PDF fX,Y(x, y). Be sure to indicate what the sample space is.¶

In [56]:
library("lattice")

pdf_function <- function(x, y) {
  a <- 1 / 800
  if (y >= 0 & y <= 2 * x) {
    return(a * 1 / 2)
  } else {
    return(0)
  }
}

x_vals <- seq(0, 40, by = 0.3)
y_vals <- seq(0, 80, by = 0.3)

z_vals <- outer(x_vals, y_vals, Vectorize(pdf_function))
z_vals[z_vals == +Inf] <- NA

persp(x_vals, y_vals, z_vals, theta = 30, phi = 50,
      xlab = "X", ylab = "Y", zlab = "PDF",
      ticktype = "detailed", col = "lightblue")

# 安装和加载ggplot2库
if (!requireNamespace("ggplot2", quietly = TRUE)) {
  install.packages("ggplot2")
}
library(ggplot2)

# 创建包含 x 和 y 的数据框
data <- expand.grid(x = seq(0, 40, 0.1), y = seq(0, 80, 0.1))
data$pdf <- with(data, 1 / 1600 * (y > x & y < 2 * x))

# 绘制二维联合概率密度函数fX,Y(x, y)
p <- ggplot(data, aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_raster(aes(fill = pdf)) +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "red") +
  geom_abline(intercept = 0, slope = 1) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 40), ylim = c(0, 80)) +
  labs(x = "x", y = "y", title = "Joint PDF fX,Y(x, y) with Y > X shading") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p)

In [17]:
# 利潤Z的密度函數 fZ(z)
fZ <- function(z) {
  ifelse(abs(z) < 40, (40 - abs(z)) / 1600, 0)
}

# 計算E[Z]
expected_Z_function <- function(z) {
  z * fZ(z)
}
expected_Z <- integrate(expected_Z_function, -40, 40)$value

# 構造Z的值
z_values <- seq(-40, 40, 0.1)
fz_values <- sapply(z_values, fZ)

# 繪製概率密度函數 fZ(z)
df <- data.frame(Z = z_values, Density = fz_values)
p3 <- ggplot(df, aes(x = Z, y = Density)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(title = sprintf("Probability Density Function of Paul's Profit Z = Y - X\nE[Z] = %.2f", expected_Z), x = "Z", y = "Density") +
  theme_minimal()

print(p3)

library("lattice")

pdf_function <- function(x, y) {
  z <- y - x
  if (abs(z) < 40) {
    return((40 - abs(z)) / 1600 * (y > x & y < 2 * x))
  } else {
    return(0)
  }
}

x_vals <- seq(0, 40, by = 0.3)
y_vals <- seq(0, 80, by = 0.3)

z_vals <- outer(x_vals, y_vals, Vectorize(pdf_function))
z_vals[z_vals == +Inf] <- NA

persp(x_vals, y_vals, z_vals, theta = 60, phi = 45,
      xlab = "X", ylab = "Y", zlab = "fZ(z)",
      ticktype = "detailed", col = "yellow")

# Required packages
library(ggplot2)

# PDF function
pdf_function <- function(x, y) {
  z <- y - x
  if (abs(z) < 40) {
    return((40 - abs(z)) / 1600 * (y > x & y < 2 * x))
  } else {
    return(0)
  }
}

# Create the grid and compute Z values
x_vals <- seq(0, 40, by = 0.1)
y_vals <- seq(0, 80, by = 0.1)
z_vals <- outer(x_vals, y_vals, Vectorize(pdf_function))

# Prepare the dataframe for ggplot
df <- expand.grid(X = x_vals, Y = y_vals)
df$Z <- as.vector(z_vals)

# Create the ggplot object
gg <- ggplot(df, aes(X, Y, fill = Z)) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "white", high = "blue") +
  theme_minimal() +
  xlab("X") +
  ylab("Y")

# Show the plot
print(gg)
